<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1605,2026]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">
<taxonomicName authority="Bernt &amp; Crampton &amp; Orfinger &amp; Albert, 2018" authorityName="Bernt &amp; Crampton &amp; Orfinger &amp; Albert" authorityYear="2018" box="[199,416,1605,1630]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Melanosternarchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[199,416,1605,1630]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Melanosternarchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Albert" authorityYear="2001" box="[878,1017,1606,1629]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Compsaraia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[878,1017,1606,1629]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Compsaraia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by four characters: 1) the absence of an L-shaped (longer longitudinally than vertically) supratemporal lateral-line canal; 2) uniform brown coloration on the head and snout vs. pale patch of low melanophore density on snout in a narrow band, anterior to the eyes and lateral to nares; 3) four mandibular canal ossicles, all ventral to the lower jaw, vs. five ossicles present, with the posterior two ossicles ventral to the preopercle; 4) dark pigmentation present on pectoral and anal fins, vs. pigmentation absent from pectoral and anal fins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="457" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1605,2026]" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">
<taxonomicName authority="Bernt &amp; Crampton &amp; Orfinger &amp; Albert, 2018" authorityName="Bernt &amp; Crampton &amp; Orfinger &amp; Albert" authorityYear="2018" box="[199,416,1821,1846]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Melanosternarchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[199,416,1821,1846]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Melanosternarchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Albert &amp; Crampton. This" authorityYear="2006" box="[735,930,1821,1846]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Pariosternarchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="456" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[735,930,1821,1846]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="456">Pariosternarchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by five characters: 1) gape extending to or beyond vertical with the eye, vs. gape not reaching vertical with eye; 2) head not expanded ventrolaterally, vs. head expanded ventrolaterally (a condition associated with expanded mandibular canal-ossicles); 3) one or no teeth present on premaxilla vs. 6 or more teeth on premaxilla; 4) teeth forming a cluster of two short, irregular rows on the posterior region of the dentary, tapering into a single row anteriorly, vs. teeth arranged in two rows on the dentary; 5) urohyal without posterior ossified blade, vs. posterior ossified blade present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">
<taxonomicName authority="Bernt &amp; Crampton &amp; Orfinger &amp; Albert, 2018" authorityName="Bernt &amp; Crampton &amp; Orfinger &amp; Albert" authorityYear="2018" box="[199,416,151,176]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Melanosternarchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[199,416,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Melanosternarchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1905" box="[954,1134,151,176]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Sternarchogiton" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[954,1134,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Sternarchogiton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except for 
<taxonomicName authority="Eigenmann &amp; Allen" authorityName="Eigenmann &amp; Allen" authorityYear="1942" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Sternarchogiton" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="porcinum">
<emphasis box="[1292,1436,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">S. porcinum</emphasis>
Eigenmann &amp; Allen
</taxonomicName>
by gape extending to or beyond vertical with the eye vs. gape not reaching vertical with eye, and from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eigenmann &amp; Allen" authorityYear="1942" box="[260,394,224,248]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Sternarchogiton" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="porcinum">
<emphasis box="[260,394,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">S. porcinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by brown pigmentation on head and sides, vs. pink to pale straw color on head and sides.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">
<taxonomicName authority="Bernt &amp; Crampton &amp; Orfinger &amp; Albert, 2018" authorityName="Bernt &amp; Crampton &amp; Orfinger &amp; Albert" authorityYear="2018" box="[199,416,260,285]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Melanosternarchus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="453" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[199,416,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Melanosternarchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eigenmann" authorityYear="1905" box="[751,901,260,285]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Sternarchella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[751,901,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Sternarchella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 1) gape extending to or beyond vertical with the eye, vs. gape not exceeding vertical with posterior naris and 2) one or no teeth on premaxilla vs. two to four rows of teeth on premaxilla.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">
Although there is not currently a diagnosis for 
<taxonomicName authority=", Melanosternarchus" authorityName="Melanosternarchus" box="[724,1080,367,392]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Porotergus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[724,848,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Porotergus</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[863,1080,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Melanosternarchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from each species in the genus. It can be differentiated from 
<taxonomicName authority="Ellis" authorityName="Ellis" authorityYear="1912" box="[708,877,404,429]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Porotergus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gimbeli">
<emphasis box="[708,819,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">P. gimbeli</emphasis>
Ellis
</taxonomicName>
by one or no teeth on the premaxilla vs. 6–8 teeth on the premaxilla; from 
<taxonomicName authority="de Santana &amp; Crampton" authorityName="de Santana &amp; Crampton" authorityYear="2010" box="[427,817,439,464]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Porotergus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="duende">
<emphasis box="[427,535,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">P. duende</emphasis>
de Santana &amp; Crampton
</taxonomicName>
by gape extending to or beyond vertical with eye; and from 
<taxonomicName authority="Ellis" authorityName="Ellis" authorityYear="1912" box="[212,407,476,501]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Porotergus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageId="6" pageNumber="457" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gymnotus">
<emphasis box="[212,347,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">P. gymnotus</emphasis>
Ellis
</taxonomicName>
by 1) dentary teeth forming a cluster of two short, irregular rows on the posterior region of the dentary, tapering into a single row anteriorly, vs. teeth arranged in two rows on the dentary and 2) one or no teeth on premaxilla vs. two or more teeth on the premaxilla.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="457" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,583,608]" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Etymology.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[342,428,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">Melano</emphasis>
from the Greek 
<emphasis box="[618,683,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">melas</emphasis>
, meaning black in reference to dark pigmentation and presence in blackwater rivers, and 
<emphasis box="[419,550,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">sternarchus</emphasis>
, a name commonly used in apteronotid taxonomy, from the Greek 
<emphasis box="[1352,1436,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">sternon</emphasis>
(chest) and 
<emphasis box="[281,356,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="457">archos</emphasis>
(rectum), referring to the anterior position of the anus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
